# Final - Physarum polycephalum

## Project Links

- Live Demo: https://biwendong.github.io/CS4300-Graphics_Simulation_Aesthetics/final/

## Overview
I'm working on the Physarum polycephalum system, and I'm rendering it in a browser.

## Technical Exploration
The system contains approximately 80,000 agents, each with a position and orientation. In each frame, the GPU executes three computational stages sequentially and schedules them via a command buffer.
During the Agent phase, each agent samples pheromone concentrations in the left, center, and right directions relative to its current direction, and adjusts its direction based on the intensity. If the center direction is the strongest, the agent continues straight while applying a small random perturbation to break symmetry; otherwise, the agent turns toward the side with the stronger signal at a fixed turn_speed. The agent then moves forward at `move_speed` and, upon reaching its new position, performs an atomicAdd operation to increment a `u32` deposit buffer. Using an `array<atomic<u32>>` prevents data races that would occur if multiple agents attempted to write to the same location simultaneously.
The diffuse stage reads the trail texture from the previous frame, applies a 3×3 box blur to it, and multiplies it by a decay factor. It then reads the deposit data generated by the agent phase, clears it via atomicExchange, and adds it to the current value. The final result is clipped to the range [0,1] and written to another trail texture. Additionally, mouse interaction injects a Gaussian-distributed pheromone source at the cursor position, allowing users to directly influence the system’s behavior.
The rendering stage uses full-screen quadrangles to convert the trail data from the simulation into the final illuminated image.

## Aesthetic Intent
The central theme of my project is bioluminescence, so I’ve used a dark background to contrast with the glowing cyan network. High-density areas appear as bright, nearly white nodes, simulating the effect of biological clusters. A bloom post-processing effect creates a soft halo around the edges of the paths.
Additionally, users can adjust the system’s behavior using parameter sliders to create smooth transitions between different forms. Mouse interaction adds a performative element, allowing users to actively guide the direction of the network’s growth.